# uv.lock is SHA-256'd byte-for-byte as a T-120 reproducible-lineage field (runlog.lockfile_hash).
# With core.autocrlf=true a fresh Windows clone would check it out as CRLF while Linux (CI/Lambda)
# gets LF, stamping different lineage hashes for byte-identical dependencies. Pin it to LF on every
# platform. (runlog.lockfile_hash also normalizes CRLF->LF in code as the primary guarantee — this
# is defense-in-depth so a fresh checkout is LF at the source.)
#
# NOTE: intentionally NOT adding `* text=auto` or any rule over experiments/** or anchors/**. Those
# sealed, tamper-evident artifacts are committed as LF but sit in the working tree as CRLF here;
# autocrlf currently re-normalizes them to LF on commit, preserving the seal. A `-text`/`text` rule
# would surface that CRLF working copy and risk committing it, breaking the seal. Leave them alone.
uv.lock text eol=lf
